                </p>
                <h3 class="subheading">A Masterclass in Design and Engineering</h3>
                <p>The Brixton Crossfire 500's appeal lies in its stunning design and premium components. The bike looks like a raw, purpose-built machine, with its exposed steel trellis frame and the signature "X" on the fuel tank. This design element, which carries across the entire Crossfire lineup, gives the bike a unique identity that is instantly recognizable. The all-LED lighting, including the round headlight with its integrated DRL, and a minimalist digital instrument cluster, all contribute to its neo-retro appeal.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Engine & Performance:</span> The heart of the Crossfire 500 is a 486cc, liquid-cooled, parallel-twin engine. This motor is expected to produce a healthy 47 bhp of power at 8,500 rpm and 43 Nm of peak torque at 6,750 rpm. This power output is a perfect balance, providing enough grunt for highway cruising while being manageable for city riding. The parallel-twin configuration ensures a smooth, refined, and linear power delivery, making the riding experience a joy. The engine is mated to a 6-speed gearbox, and the throttle response is expected to be crisp and predictable.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Premium Hardware:</span> What truly sets the Crossfire 500 apart is its use of premium, top-shelf components. The bike is expected to feature fully adjustable Kayaba (KYB) suspension at both the front and rear. This is a rare feature in this segment and will allow riders to fine-tune the bike's handling and comfort to their liking. Braking duties are handled by high-performance J.Juan calipers, which are a part of the Bosch dual-channel ABS system, ensuring excellent stopping power and enhanced safety.</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Riding Ergonomics:</span> The Crossfire 500 is designed to offer a comfortable yet engaging riding position. The Crossfire 500 X, the roadster variant, is expected to have a seat height of around 795 mm, making it accessible to a wide range of riders. The Crossfire 500 XC, the scrambler variant, will feature a taller stance with a higher ground clearance and a seat height of approximately 839 mm, making it more capable on rough roads. Both bikes will ride on spoke wheels, with the 500 X getting 17-inch wheels at both ends, and the 500 XC featuring a 19-inch front and a 17-inch rear wheel, shod with high-quality Pirelli tires.</li>
                </ul>
